% \subsection{Generative Reward Model (GRM)}

% From early experiments in the UX prediction, we find that mainstream reasoning models struggle to accurately capture user feedback signals and exhibit strong bias in their judgments. To enable practical automated evaluation, we therefore propose to train a pointwise Generative Reward Model (GRM) on user feedback data. To mitigate potential data contamination effects, we sample training data from a temporally disjoint period of dialogue logs, ensuring no overlap with the evaluation set.



\section{Results and Discussion}

In this section, we progressively analyze LLM capabilities from user feedback prediction to response generation, complemented by key ablation studies for each task. Due to page limits, full implementation details are provided in Appendix~\ref{appendix:implementation}, while complete experimental results are reported in Appendix~\ref{appendix:full-results}. Since a key research question is to understand how UX evolves with model capability, we select 27 representative models following two principles: coverage and scale, spanning major model families, capability levels, and release generations.


\subsection{Task 1: UX Judgment}

While Task 1 is framed as a binary judgment, Table~\ref{tab:main_result} reveals largely negative results across models. The best-performing zero-shot model (Claude Opus 4.7) achieves 75.3\% overall accuracy, with a good accuracy of 89.1\% but a substantially lower bad accuracy of 61.5\%. This imbalance becomes more pronounced for weaker models: DeepSeek-R1 reaches 98.6\% good accuracy, while its bad accuracy collapses to 18.3\%.

\paragraph{Finding 1: Frontier LLMs exhibit a strong and systematic positive bias.}
Consistent with prior observations that AI models tend to favor AI-generated content \cite{doi:10.1073/pnas.2415697122}, all 27 models exhibit a strong bias toward positive judgments and substantially under-detect negative interactions. Since UXBench is class-balanced, a well-calibrated evaluator should achieve comparable performance across both classes. We hypothesize that this failure is driven by the nature of UXBench, where negative samples are primarily grounded in experience-oriented signals such as verbosity, weak engagement, and emotional insensitivity, rather than the factual or lexical errors that LLMs are more familiar with. These results suggest that current models remain weak at recognizing subtle interaction failures, highlighting a key area for improvement.

% \begin{figure}
%     \centering
%     \includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{floats/fig_task1.png}
%     \caption{Performance of LLM judges on user feedback prediction, .}
%     \label{fig:task1_leaderboard}
% \end{figure}


\paragraph{Binary vs. Three-class Prediction.} To justify the advantage of unified binary judgment, we evaluate models under a three-class setting (\textit{positive} / \textit{neutral} / \textit{negative}). Introducing a neutral option consistently reduces overall performance, with strong models like Claude Opus 4.6 assigning 385 out of 1,000 BAD instances to neutral, resulting in only 41.8\% BAD accuracy. Overall, the results reveal a strong ``neutral escape'' phenomenon, in which models avoid committing to negative judgments under uncertainty, highlighting that the observed positive bias in UX prediction is more severe beyond binary settings. Model-specific behaviors are provided in Appendix~\ref{appendix:task1_ablation_three_classes}.



