\section{Conclusion}

This paper presents \textbf{UXBench}, the first benchmark grounded in real user feedback signals for evaluating AI assistants beyond capability-oriented proxies. Built from large-scale interaction logs, UXBench defines three tasks covering UX judgment, response generation, and failure recovery, and reveals consistent gaps across 27 frontier LLMs, including systematic positive bias, self-preference, and a weak-scaling trend that indicates a potential mismatch between model development and user-perceivable utility. UXBench advances user-centric model evaluation by emphasizing interaction quality over raw capabilities, calling for future model development to optimize user-preference alignment and equip models with more robust response strategies. Furthermore, UXBench motivates future LLM evaluation design to better leverage real user feedback signals and alleviate the shortage of explainable ground-truth annotations, enabling fully automated model evaluation at scale.




\section*{Limitations}

While this paper provides comprehensive insights into user experience evaluation, several limitations remain. First, UXBench is primarily grounded in the Chinese language and involves Chinese-specific domains, such as Chinese companies and support for Chinese students. Although comparisons with three public English benchmarks show broadly consistent patterns, cultural and linguistic biases may still persist. Extending to multilingual and cross-cultural settings would improve its generalizability.

Second, the response generation task focuses on single-turn generation conditioned on multi-turn dialogue history. This design enables controlled and scalable comparison across models, but does not fully capture continuous multi-turn interactions, where user experience may evolve over time. Future work can incorporate user simulators or interactive evaluation protocols to study UX dynamics.

Third, UXBench focuses primarily on frontier models to better reflect current high-end UX capabilities, overlooking open-weight small language models. Although empirical results on two Qwen models show generally poor performance and the scaling trend, these findings may not extend to other model families.

