We study closed-menu natural-language recommendation. Let the current restaurant menu be $M=\{d_1,d_2,\ldots,d_n\}$, where each dish $d_i$ has observable menu information such as name, category, ingredient description, and explicit menu cues. Given a request $x$, the system outputs a ranked Top-$N$ list with short explanations:
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
    f(x, M) \rightarrow \mathcal{R}_N(x, M) = \big\{ &(d^{(1)}, e^{(1)}), \dots, \\
    &(d^{(N)}, e^{(N)}) \big\}.
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
Each $d^{(k)}\in M$ must be an available menu dish, and $e^{(k)}$ must be grounded in menu evidence. For analysis, we describe each request in terms of three components: hard constraints $C(x)$, health-oriented or lifestyle-medicine-adjacent goals $H(x)$, and soft preferences $P(x)$. For example, in a real test request, ``Post-gym and hungry, so I want something with enough protein but not fried'', $C(x)$ includes avoiding fried food, $H(x)$ includes high-protein eating, and $P(x)$ includes a preference for a filling protein option. This factorization characterizes the task and evaluation; the final recommender is not a hand-coded rule-only ranker.

