\title{LifeMenu: A Lifestyle-Medicine-Oriented Vertical Model for Menu-Grounded Restaurant Ordering}
\author{}
\date{}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
A restaurant menu is a small but consequential action space: a diner can only order dishes that are available, while dietary needs are often stated in loose natural language. A request such as ``something light, high-protein, and without seafood'' requires the system to preserve hard exclusions, balance health-oriented preferences, and justify its choices using only evidence visible on the menu. This setting differs from open-domain food recommendation and recipe search, where models can suggest foods outside the immediate ordering context. We present \textsc{LifeMenu}, a menu-grounded restaurant-ordering system for lifestyle-medicine-adjacent dietary preference support. \textsc{LifeMenu} represents a real restaurant menu as a closed action space, builds auditable evidence cards for dishes, and generates structured Top-$N$ recommendations with concise menu-grounded explanations. For practical deployment, we distill the behavior of a strong OpenAI route into a local Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct student using QLoRA. In blind human evaluation, the resulting local system is competitive with strong online LLMs, while supporting controllable, privacy-preserving, and lower-cost restaurant-side recommendation that stays faithful to the current menu. \textsc{LifeMenu} supports dietary preference matching at ordering time and does not provide clinical nutrition advice.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Food choices are part of everyday lifestyle management, but many dietary decisions occur in concrete and constrained settings. Restaurant ordering is one such setting: a diner chooses not from an unlimited food space, but from the dishes currently available on a menu. Users also express ordering needs in natural language, such as asking for a lighter lunch, a high-protein dinner after exercise, a blood-sugar-friendly rice option, or a noodle dish without seafood. Such requests often combine hard exclusions, health-oriented goals, staple or protein preferences, taste preferences, and contextual dining needs.

\begin{figure*}[t]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=.82\textwidth]{fig1.png}
    \caption{Overview of \textsc{LifeMenu}. The system treats the restaurant menu as a closed action space, constructs evidence cards for available dishes, distills a selected teacher route into a local Qwen QLoRA student, and evaluates outputs with human judgments under the same fixed-menu setting.}
    \label{fig:overview}
\end{figure*}

This setting makes restaurant ordering a distinctive natural-language recommendation problem. The system must map a free-form request to a ranked list of feasible menu actions. Each recommended item must be a valid dish in the current menu. Explicit exclusions, such as avoiding seafood, pork, dairy, mushrooms, or spicy food, must be preserved. Health-oriented goals, such as ``light'', ``not greasy'', ``high-protein'', or ``blood-sugar-friendly'', must be balanced against softer preferences such as rice, noodles, vegetables, or chicken. Explanations should remain grounded in observable menu evidence, because hallucinated ingredients or unsupported nutrition claims can mislead users at the point of ordering.

We connect this setting to the dietary dimension of lifestyle medicine in a narrow operational sense. \textsc{LifeMenu} does not provide clinical nutrition advice, diagnosis, or treatment. It supports ordering-time dietary preference matching near lifestyle-medicine goals, such as calorie awareness, blood-sugar-friendly selection, protein adequacy, lower-grease preference, and ingredient avoidance. Lifestyle medicine is commonly framed around lifestyle factors, including nutrition and other behavioral pillars \citep{lippman2024foundations,reddy2019urgent}. Our goal is not to replace clinicians or dietitians, but to translate everyday lifestyle-oriented dietary intent into feasible, menu-grounded restaurant choices.

Prior work on recommender systems, food recommendation, and dietary support has studied personalization, health awareness, and explanation \citep{adomavicius2005next,tran2018overview,trattner2017investigating,min2020food,chen2021personalized,zhang2020explainable}. Recent language-model-based systems also show that dietary needs are often expressed through free text \citep{li2025llms}. However, much of this work targets recipes, diet coaching, nutrition question answering, or open-domain food spaces. The closed-menu restaurant setting has received less attention despite its small, fixed, directly actionable candidate space.

We address this gap with \textsc{LifeMenu}, a menu-grounded natural-language recommendation system for restaurant ordering. Each dish is represented by a menu evidence card with a dish identifier, category, ingredient evidence, restricted-ingredient signals, health cues, and readable tags. Given a user request and the fixed menu, the system returns a structured Top-$N$ recommendation list with short explanations. Both recommendation and explanation must stay within the observable menu action space.

A key question is whether a local model can keep the menu-grounded behavior of a stronger online LLM route while meeting the practical needs of restaurant-side deployment. We use a teacher--student workflow: a selected OpenAI route generates structured supervision over the real menu, and a local Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct student is adapted with QLoRA \citep{yang2025qwen25,dettmers2023qlora,hu2022lora}. The adapted student is then integrated into \textsc{LifeMenu} as the local recommendation engine. At inference time, it receives only the system instruction, user request, and menu evidence, and generates the structured recommendation schema without teacher outputs or external model calls. This local design reduces dependence on online services, improves privacy control, and enables faster, lower-cost serving after training.

This paper makes three contributions. To our knowledge, \textsc{LifeMenu} is the first system that studies lifestyle-medicine-adjacent natural-language ordering under a fixed real restaurant menu, where all recommendations must be directly orderable dishes grounded in observable menu evidence. We propose a menu-grounded distillation workflow that organizes static menu evidence into auditable dish cards, uses a strong teacher route to generate structured recommendation supervision, and distills this behavior into a local Qwen7B model with QLoRA. The local student supports lower marginal serving cost, stronger privacy control, and reduced dependence on external API calls. We also provide a blind human evaluation on 100 test requests with six raters and six systems, showing that the adapted local model clearly improves over the unadapted local baseline and is competitive with strong online LLM baselines under the same fixed-menu setting.

\section{Related Work}

\paragraph{Food recommendation and dietary support.}
Food recommendation extends standard recommendation with food-specific constraints, nutrition concerns, and user health goals \citep{tran2018overview,min2020food}. Prior work has studied healthy food choices, recipe recommendation, nutrition-aware ranking, and constrained food recommendation over knowledge graphs \citep{trattner2017investigating,chen2021personalized}. These studies motivate recommendation beyond taste preference alone, but they largely focus on recipes, meal planning, or general healthy food support rather than immediate restaurant ordering under a closed menu. Recent work on LLMs in nutrition further shows both the opportunity and risk of using general-purpose models for dietary reasoning \citep{li2025llms}. \textsc{LifeMenu} targets a more focused but operationally stricter setting: the output must be a ranked list of directly orderable dishes from the current menu.

\paragraph{Grounded language interfaces and LLM recommenders.}
Grounded language systems link user utterances to constrained actions, structured states, or database-backed operations \citep{liu2024suql,xu2025schema,xu2025sqlwoz}. This perspective is closely related to menu-grounded recommendation, where dish identifiers form the action space and menu evidence defines what can be recommended. LLMs have also been explored as end-to-end recommenders, conversational recommenders, and recommendation agents \citep{ren2025easyrec,tajiri2025refining,peng2025survey}. Explanation remains important for user-facing recommendation \citep{ma2024xrec,zhang2025enhancing}. Our work treats restaurant ordering as grounded recommendation over a closed menu and uses distillation to transfer the behavior of a strong online LLM route into a local model for deployment.

\section{System Design}

\subsection{Task Definition}

We study closed-menu natural-language recommendation. Let the current restaurant menu be $M=\{d_1,d_2,\ldots,d_n\}$, where each dish $d_i$ has observable menu information such as name, category, ingredient description, and explicit menu cues. Given a request $x$, the system outputs a ranked Top-$N$ list with short explanations:
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
    f(x, M) \rightarrow \mathcal{R}_N(x, M) = \big\{ &(d^{(1)}, e^{(1)}), \dots, \\
    &(d^{(N)}, e^{(N)}) \big\}.
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
Each $d^{(k)}\in M$ must be an available menu dish, and $e^{(k)}$ must be grounded in menu evidence. For analysis, we describe each request in terms of three components: hard constraints $C(x)$, health-oriented or lifestyle-medicine-adjacent goals $H(x)$, and soft preferences $P(x)$. For example, in a real test request, ``Post-gym and hungry, so I want something with enough protein but not fried'', $C(x)$ includes avoiding fried food, $H(x)$ includes high-protein eating, and $P(x)$ includes a preference for a filling protein option. This factorization characterizes the task and evaluation; the final recommender is not a hand-coded rule-only ranker.

