\begin{abstract}
A restaurant menu is a small but consequential action space: a diner can only order dishes that are available, while dietary needs are often stated in loose natural language. A request such as ``something light, high-protein, and without seafood'' requires the system to preserve hard exclusions, balance health-oriented preferences, and justify its choices using only evidence visible on the menu. This setting differs from open-domain food recommendation and recipe search, where models can suggest foods outside the immediate ordering context. We present \textsc{LifeMenu}, a menu-grounded restaurant-ordering system for lifestyle-medicine-adjacent dietary preference support. \textsc{LifeMenu} represents a real restaurant menu as a closed action space, builds auditable evidence cards for dishes, and generates structured Top-$N$ recommendations with concise menu-grounded explanations. For practical deployment, we distill the behavior of a strong OpenAI route into a local Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct student using QLoRA. In blind human evaluation, the resulting local system is competitive with strong online LLMs, while supporting controllable, privacy-preserving, and lower-cost restaurant-side recommendation that stays faithful to the current menu. \textsc{LifeMenu} supports dietary preference matching at ordering time and does not provide clinical nutrition advice. (see \ref{fig:nonexistent_label_xyz_4d44d6})
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Food choices are part of everyday lifestyle management, but many dietary decisions occur in concrete and constrained settings. Restaurant ordering is one such setting: a diner chooses not from an unlimited food space, but from the dishes currently available on a menu. Users also express ordering needs in natural language, such as asking for a lighter lunch, a high-protein dinner after exercise, a blood-sugar-friendly rice option, or a noodle dish without seafood. Such requests often combine hard exclusions, health-oriented goals, staple or protein preferences, taste preferences, and contextual dining needs.

\begin{figure*}[t]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=.82\textwidth]{fig1.png}
    \caption{Overview of \textsc{LifeMenu}. The system treats the restaurant menu as a closed action space, constructs evidence cards for available dishes, distills a selected teacher route into a local Qwen QLoRA student, and evaluates outputs with human judgments under the same fixed-menu setting.}
    \label{fig:overview}
\end{figure*}

This setting makes restaurant ordering a distinctive natural-language recommendation problem. The system must map a free-form request to a ranked list of feasible menu actions. Each recommended item must be a valid dish in the current menu. Explicit exclusions, such as avoiding seafood, pork, dairy, mushrooms, or spicy food, must be preserved. Health-oriented goals, such as ``light'', ``not greasy'', ``high-protein'', or ``blood-sugar-friendly'', must be balanced against softer preferences such as rice, noodles, vegetables, or chicken. Explanations should remain grounded in observable menu evidence, because hallucinated ingredients or unsupported nutrition claims can mislead users at the point of ordering.

We connect this setting to the dietary dimension of lifestyle medicine in a narrow operational sense. \textsc{LifeMenu} does not provide clinical nutrition advice, diagnosis, or treatment. It supports ordering-time dietary preference matching near lifestyle-medicine goals, such as calorie awareness, blood-sugar-friendly selection, protein adequacy, lower-grease preference, and ingredient avoidance. Lifestyle medicine is commonly framed around lifestyle factors, including nutrition and other behavioral pillars \citep{lippman2024foundations,reddy2019urgent}. Our goal is not to replace clinicians or dietitians, but to translate everyday lifestyle-oriented dietary intent into feasible, menu-grounded restaurant choices.

