Our method distills menu-grounded recommendation behavior from a strong teacher route into a local Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct student with QLoRA. The adapted student can be served locally, reducing marginal inference cost, improving privacy control, and avoiding repeated external API calls.

Blind human evaluation on 100 test requests with six raters shows that Qwen QLoRA Student improves clearly over Qwen Base and is competitive with strong online LLM baselines, achieving the highest observed mean score, although its margin over the strongest online baseline is small under paired bootstrap analysis. Rule-based automatic recommendation diagnostics show the same supporting trend: the student ranks highest on Top-1 intent hit, Top-5 intent coverage, and rank-weighted request--dish relevance. These results show that a locally deployable 7B adapter can be competitive in a focused, evidence-grounded restaurant-ordering task while reducing marginal inference cost, improving privacy control, and reducing dependence on external API availability.

