\begin{abstract}
A restaurant menu is a small but consequential action space: a diner can only order dishes that are available, while dietary needs are often stated in loose natural language. A request such as ``something light, high-protein, and without seafood'' requires the system to preserve hard exclusions, balance health-oriented preferences, and justify its choices using only evidence visible on the menu. This setting differs from open-domain food recommendation and recipe search, where models can suggest foods outside the immediate ordering context. We present \textsc{LifeMenu}, a menu-grounded restaurant-ordering system for lifestyle-medicine-adjacent dietary preference support. \textsc{LifeMenu} represents a real restaurant menu as a closed action space, builds auditable evidence cards for dishes, and generates structured Top-$N$ recommendations with concise menu-grounded explanations. For practical deployment, we distill the behavior of a strong OpenAI route into a local Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct student using QLoRA. In blind human evaluation, the resulting local system is competitive with strong online LLMs, while supporting controllable, privacy-preserving, and lower-cost restaurant-side recommendation that stays faithful to the current menu. \textsc{LifeMenu} supports dietary preference matching at ordering time and does not provide clinical nutrition advice.
